#Granger Causality Analysis of Insect Abundance Trends in Germany
#The Effect of Soil, Vegetation, Weather, and Landscape Variables on Insect Time Series
##Project Description
This project performs Granger Causality analysis to investigate potential effects of landscape, soil, weather, vegetation, and agricultural data on insect abundance trends.

There are 7 types of input datasets

*BExIS Insect Abundance Data for Grasslands1 and Forests2

*Annual weighted mean Crop Yield and Area (German Yield Data)3

*Annual Crop-specific Fertilizer Application Rates (Fertilizer Maps)4

*Annual Landscape Structure Metrics (“Germany Mosaic”) (Germany Mosaic)5

*Monthly Soil Moisture Index (SMI) (German Drought Monitor)6

*Monthly Remote Sensing Indicators (NDVI, NDMI, NIRv) (USGS Landsat7 - GEE)7

*Monthly Weather and Soil Temperature Data (BExIS Climate Data)8

Data were pre-processed by aggregating or clipping to match the extent of the Biodiversity Exploratories, where the insect data was sampled. There are three Biodiversity Exploratory sites, Schwäbische Alb (ALB), Hainich-Dün (HAI) and Schorfheide-Chorin (SCH). Granger causality tests were applied at monthly and yearly resolutions, after checking stationarity using ADF and KPSS tests. Non-stationary series were detrended and/or differenced before testing. If statistically processed data were made stationary, they were put together with orignally stationary data, and then a second round of Granger Causality Testing was applied. As a final step, a sensitivity analysis was applied by visual analysis.

##Repositories
The input data and output tables and plots of the analysis are available at the OSF Repository. The R scripts are available at the GitHub Repository.

##Structure of input data
The input datasets are to be found in the data folder:

